group_dy8ma60/Description_003: Oldest parts of the site = south and southwest. Mound area is newer (more pirangua). Immediately on the other side of the river there was ceramic -- possibly different people or time period but possibly related. Silty sand. Mound is 1.5m ish tall and 5 m long. Contemporary occupants of Garachine continue to dump waste here -- but many different species also that previously were not seen (in contemporary areas around houses, for example). Site covers an area of roughly 25m x 35m.

group_sj61b88/Description_009: Soil underneath = reddish brown but soil above = brownish black (tierra negra, seems like barrial -- cracks when it is dry). Wider from 4th terrace on. 16 terraces, heights are variable. soil is way more reddish at the top. some are disturbed from modern human and cow trampling. Irregular top -- terrace before coming down again. NW side slopes down gradually but only 4 steps. Really terraced part (SE) discharges into stream (where you get the most water). First samples taken from between terraces 6 and 7 (horizontal tubes T7 and T8). Terrace 7 width =80cm, terrace 6 width =60cm, depth between them =140cm.

group_ve9cv03/Description_001: At a place 1 to 1 1/2 kilometre distant from the river's mouth, a natural selection of one of its banks has formed from the erosive action of the river. The river flows nearly due north to south, and archaeological deposits were found on its west bank, over an area extending to a length of about 75 m. In the north end of the old dwelling site, at a height of about 1 m above water at ebb-tide, and more or less awash at flood-tide, there is a stratum, almost of the character of cement, containing shells (of uniform type) admixed with a low proportion of pottery fragments. Farther up on the river above this site no traces of ancient habitation were found, but towards its mouth discovered pottery fragments, although sparingly, in the present river bed.

group_ve9cv03/Site_name: Fuerte de San Geronimo de Yaviza
group_ve9cv03/Description_001: unidentified/Fort is oriented to river -- 35 degrees NE? La provincia de Darien cuenta con Casas Fuertes, construidas por los españoles entre los años de 1760 a 1785, que estaban equipadas con cañones, protegidas por soldados y tenían como propósito repeler los ataques indígenas, de corsarios, filibusteros y piratas, quienes constantemente atacban las poblaciones ocupadas por España durante la época del Virreinato de Nueva Granada. Uno de los fuertes construidos por los españoles es el Fuerte San Geronimo de Yaviza (río Chucunaque), reconocido hoy día como Patrimonio Histórico de la Humanidad.
